  "doc_id": "21065",
  "text": "Similar results have come from Chile, where a short-term study had documented peaks in populations of rodents, especially the dominant species Octodon degu, following El Niño [CITATION_1] ). However, longer-term records and comparisons across sites revealed that El Niños were not invariably followed by increases in degu populations [CITATION_2] . In fact, spatially separated populations showed dynamics that were out of phase with each other and often out of phase with ENSO. This observation led Lima and colleagues (1999) to propose that degu populations exhibit chaotic dynamics.",
